Getting the data into Python¶

As with most visualization and analysis, the first process is reading the data.

If you look at a tool, like ParaView or VisIt, they have many, many readers to deal with all of the custom formats.

Thus, the first task of any data analysis is the getting the data into your tool. A data analyst, you'll do this so many times, you get sick of it.

This is one of the reasons we will talk about SQLite -- once you have created a implementation, your data can be read into any tool that supports SQLite.

Fortran data¶

In the case of our simple simulation, actually the format is quite simple for the purposes of our exercise.

We'll talk about the simulation later, but for now, all you need to know that it is simulating a flat plate that is cooling off over time.

It's tab/space separated values. But, the data is written out in separate files per time step and process (there are 4 processes that computed this simulation).

So, we'll write a simple function that given a time step and processor, we'll read the data into lists.

As a note, we could have used Pandas, because this is close enough to tab separated values. That's typically not the case though for abitrary scientific data.

Custom reader¶

read_processor_time will read the output from a processor for a particular time step.

It will return it as a tuple of three columns, i, j, h for temperature. This is a structure of arrays (SoA), or columnar -- I prefer SoA over array of structures (AoS), and most plotting tools will want the data in columnar format, anyways.

In [3]:
def read_processor_time(prefix, p, t):
    # open file
    f = open((prefix + '/output.%d.%d') % (p, t))
    i, j, h = [], [], []
    line = f.readline()
    # until there are no more lines
    while line != '':
        line = line.split()
        # add them to i, j, h
        i.append(int(line[0]))
        j.append(int(line[1]))
        h.append(float(line[2]))
        line = f.readline()
    # return (i, j, h)
    return i, j, h

Plotting the data¶

There are several plotting tools for Python. In particular, I'll use Bokeh because it looks a bit nicer than Matplotlib and it's interactive if you are using a browser.

In [5]:
import numpy
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_notebook, show

output_notebook()
Loading BokehJS ...

image_processor_time will display an image of the flat plate, given a processor and a time step.

In [6]:
def image_processor_time(prefix, p, t):
    # read our data
    i, j, h = read_processor_time(prefix, p, t)
    
    # sort h
    ijh = zip(i, j, h)
    max_i = max(i)
    ijh = sorted(ijh, key=lambda item: item[0] + item[1] * max_i)
    h = [item[2] for item in ijh]    
    
    # reshape our data into a 2D array (h is already in the correct order)
    h = numpy.array(h).reshape(len(numpy.unique(i)), len(numpy.unique(j)), 1)

    # show it
    fig = figure()
    fig.image([h], -1, -1, 1, 1)
    show(fig)

Reading all of the data¶

Though, we have a problem, at least for this particular simulation output, each processor wrote it's data individually into separate files per time step.

This is actually quite common in large-parallel processing because it is hard to coordinate meta-data at the file system level (causing global locking and slowing down writes).

read_time will use our read_processor_time function to be able to read all of the data.

In [8]:
def read_time(prefix, t):
    # read processor 0-4
    i0, j0, h0 = read_processor_time(prefix, 0, t)
    i1, j1, h1 = read_processor_time(prefix, 1, t)
    i2, j2, h2 = read_processor_time(prefix, 2, t)
    i3, j3, h3 = read_processor_time(prefix, 3, t)
    # return the union of them all
    return i0 + i1 + i2 + i3, j0 + j1 + j2 + j3, h0 + h1 + h2 + h3

And image_time will show an image for all processors of the data for a particular time step.

One important thing is that now h is unsorted, with respect to the data as a whole. So we need to sort it by i and j.

In [9]:
def image_time(prefix, t):
    # read our data, but h is unsorted by i and j
    i, j, h = read_time(prefix, t)
    
    # sort h
    ijh = zip(i, j, h)
    max_i = max(i)
    ijh = sorted(ijh, key=lambda item: item[0] + item[1] * max_i)
    h = [item[2] for item in ijh]
    
    # reshape our data into a 2D array
    h = numpy.array(h).reshape(len(numpy.unique(i)), len(numpy.unique(j)), 1)
    
    # show it
    fig = figure()
    fig.image([h], -1, -1, 1, 1)
    show(fig)
In [10]:

Querying & slicing¶

Here, I have a whole treatise on why I do not like data frames. This isn't in the main presentation, but I left it here for posterity.

At this point, if you want to do queries, you have to write a lot of code extracting the relevant portions of the arrays. This is problematic because now you've written one time analysis code (with potentially a lot of implementation just to read the data) for a particular tool. What if now you want to do your analysis in R?

Most jump into Pandas or R data frames, or something else similar that looks like data frames.

We're not going to use data frames, instead we're going straight to representing the data directly as relational data.

Soapbox #1¶

Why I don't like Data Frames

  • It still requires a reader to copy your data set into a data frame
  • Data frame syntax is literally the worst thing ever
  • If you want to do a query, you create a boolean vector that is used for index slicing
    • A = [data]
    • I = [some condition on A]
      • I is a boolean vector with the same "shape" as A, i.e., it's a boolean mask
    • subset_A = A[I]
  • Complete example:
    • A = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
    • I = A > 3
    • A[I] => [4, 5, 6]
    • A[A > 3]) => "[4, 5, 6]"

It's very imperative and it becomes difficult to chain filters

  • With array notation, it is hard to combine (chain) them, because you are in "imperative" land
    • B = A[A > 3]
    • C = B[B < 6]
    • D = C[C % 2 == 0]
    • Intermediate memory for B and C generated
    • What if I remove "B" or "C" to change my query? I just broke my program
    • Or: A[(A > 3) & (A < 6) & (A % 2 == 0)]
      • The size of A isn't changed (reduced) until the [] evaluation
  • Combining multiple filters and queries becomes very messy
  • Pandas and R data frames are in-memory only
    • Our example data isn't large, but what if you want to do a query based on time?
    • Why not use Spark? We could, but I want to show SQLite as a starting point
      • Spark is more (key, value) oriented than relational
        • There is Flink
        • I know that Python and R have Spark bindings, but let's stick with SQLite
      • Spark does have the ingest problem
        • Have to copy data into its RDD format
        • Not feasible for large-scale scientific data
    • Dask is an out-of-core solution for Pandas
      • But it primarily uses the data frame syntax (UGH) -- rather than Spark functional combinators
      • And its Spark-like form, aka bags, cannot do joins!
  • SQL (and SQLite) is better:
    • data sits at rest
      • no ingest!
        • a huge win for our scientific users, they cannot or will not copy their data or change formats
        • works without a server (in supercomputing environment generally hard to run database services)
    • no array slicing, but uses sets of tuples and relations on those sets
      • relational algebra and database semantics, easy to filter
    • database query semantics overlap with higher-order combinators
      • map, filter, transform, reduce, etc.
        • R has dplyr that turns SQL database access into a higher-order combinator programming
          • combined with ggplot you can make transformations from data to image
      • We'll talk about this later
    • hews closer to data parallel paradigms
      • We'll talk about this later, too
    • out-of-core, i.e. streaming data
      • lazy evaluation - it does not execute until you ask it to
      • SQLite is always streaming when it is executing a query
      • You can create infinite lists/sets in SQLite
    • recursive queries (Turing complete)
    • portable to anything that reads SQLite (if it has extensions enabled)

SQLite extensions¶

One thing I need to mention is that it does require that the SQLite version that is compiled into your tool has "load extension" enabled. This means that you can load a shared library (.so/.dylib/.dll) into SQLite.

This provides run-time extension capabilities to your tool, like virtual tables and custom SQL functions.

This is necessary for our reader.

  • In Python it requires either
    • building sqlite yourself because it is not consistent if it is enabled
      • I have an issue open for Anaconda Python to have it enabled there
    • or using apsw, another SQLite module, has it enabled by default
  • R has it enabled in RSQLite
    • though, the R that is on this virtual machine was built from github because the CRAN version is old
    • the below virtual table implementation requires >= 3.14 SQLite, so I needed to build it
In [ ]:

One Reader to Rule Them All¶

A virtual table for our data¶

I've created a "virtual table" for our data set. This means we can now access our data via SQLite, and hence in any tool that supports SQLite.

In our case, this particular virtual table exposes the data set as a table heat with columns i, j, heat AND also processor, and time: I joined all of the time steps (separate files) into a table, so now we don't have to load individual time steps.

For example, I can do a query on time = some time step and it will only return the data from that time step, i.e., only read that file.

SQLite virtual tables allow you to express any data set as a relational data to the SQLite interpreter -- as long as you can figure out a way to represent it as structured data... which is true for 99% of scientific data.

Generally in scientific computing, we have a grids (like i, j, k) or cells and points with attribute data, which are structured -- these can be represented as tables. Even experimental data is very structured: generally, there are inputs (parameters) and outputs (the measurements of those experiments).

But, SQLite virtual tables are useful for any data set, not just scientific data.

Don't think if you aren't doing scientific computing that you can't use SQLite virtual tables. There are multiple existing SQLite virtual table implementations, such as CSV, text search, JSON(!), etc.

Soapbox # 2¶

I would argue that most data sets ARE structured, and it is rare that a data set is truly unstructured, i.e., key-value pairs (like metadata). If feel like that unstructured data appears when time and effort is not made to create a structure (schema) for ingest, but then the price is paid in the implementation. (I know I've offended someone just now)

For instance, learning how to "normalize" data is a huge skill for understanding structured data.

Also, unstructured data tends to lead to interpreted languages, since it requires a parsing, DSL, or ADT solution, because the data is hard to "statically type".

I have strong negative opinions about noSQL/unstructured stores, and this talk is going to be structured only -- if you want a religious discussion, we can have one over a beer later (you're buying).

Loading ORTRTA into Python¶

Here, I'm using apsw (Another Python SQLite Wrapper), that allows us to load our virtual table implementation.

In [11]:
import apsw
db = apsw.Connection(':memory:')
# load our extension
db.enableloadextension(True)
db.loadextension(prefix + '/sqlite/heat')
# load our data set as a table
cursor = db.cursor()
cursor.execute('create virtual table fortran using heat("%s/fortran/data/")' % prefix)
Out[11]:
<apsw.Cursor at 0x7efcc447d030>

pragma table_info gives us our schema that we created over our data set.

In particular, time lets us query by time step. This allows us to access all files as they were written out by time step. If we were to do this with a custom reader, we'd have to implement a facility to handle time.

Also, time and processor are really part of the file name of the data set. This is just handled as normal data that is exposed and we can query on it.

Creating plots with queries¶

Now, we can create the images that we did before. I'll create a small function that turns any query into a list of lists for easy manipulation in Python.

One thing to note that in Python (and other versions), that a query returns a cursor, which is an iterator. This way we can use list generators to iterate over everything in a query.

In [17]:
def query_to_list(conn, query):
    # get a cursor for the query
    cursor = conn.cursor()
    cursor.execute(query)
    
    # get the first row to create an Array of Structures (AoS) -- a list of lists
    lists = [[i] for i in cursor.fetchone()]
    # iterate for the query and append the data to all lists (arrays)
    for row in cursor:
        lists = [l + [column] for l, column in zip(lists, row)]
        
    return lists

A simple function that given a query, create an image for that query.

One difference from the example before was that we read the data in, and did a sort. Here, we can have SQLite do the sort for us with an order by i, j.

Also, another difference is that we don't have to worry about reading in separate processors for the Fortran data. Since processor is just a relationship, it will be grabbed with everything else and we can drop that column since we don't care.

For example a query select heat from fortran where time = 1000 order by i, j will return all of the heat values, ordered by i, j, for time step 1000. The processor column is just dropped since we don't care.

In [18]:
def image_query(conn, query, x, y):
    # notice we don't need to sort h, because the query will sort it with an "order by"
    h = query_to_list(conn, query + ' order by i, j')
    
    # reshape our data into a 2D array
    h = numpy.array(h).reshape(x, y, 1)
    
    # show it
    fig = figure()
    fig.image([h], -1, -1, 1, 1)
    show(fig)

Get the dimensions of the images.

In [19]:
x, y = query_to_list(db, 'select max(i) - min(i) + 1, max(j) - min(j) + 1 from fortran where time = 3000')
x = x[0]
y = y[0]
print(x, y)

Now, let's plot the image where time is step 3000.

The SQLite virtual table implementation over this data set has an index on time - so it will only read time step 3000, i.e., it will skip reading other time step data. We'll talk later about building indices for columns when we look at the implementation.

SQLite query processor will try to optimize the number of reads that it has to execute to fetch your query, such that it will only try to fetch data where time = 3000.

In [20]:
image_query(db, 'select heat from fortran where time = 3000', x, y)

More fun tricks¶

Now, we can do more interesting plots and querying the data, like "what's the maximum temperature over time"?

First, we'll just create a small function that creates line plots, plot_query.

In [21]:
def plot_query(conn, query, x_scale="linear", y_scale="linear"):
    x, y = query_to_list(conn, query)

    fig = figure(x_axis_type=x_scale, y_axis_type=y_scale)
    # also, we cheat here and don't have to sort x
    # most plotting tools will do this for you, if you give it
    # two columns, it assumes y is dependent on x, and sorts x and y by x
    fig.line(x, y)
    show(fig)

Given our Fortran data, here is the query to plot the max temperature over time.

In [22]:
plot_query(db, "select time, max(heat) from fortran group by time", y_scale="log")

So, that's interesting, let's now ask "what does the Scala version look like over time?"

First, we'll create a new virtual table using the Scala data set. It's as simple as pointing it to the new directory with our ORTRTA.

In [ ]:

Since the data are in two plots, it's hard to compare them. We'll make a simple function to plot multiple queries as line plots in the same plot, plot_queries.

In [25]:
def plot_queries(conn, queries, x_scale="linear", y_scale="linear"):
    fig = figure(x_axis_type=x_scale, y_axis_type=y_scale)
    
    # for each query, execute it and create a line plot
    for query, num in zip(queries, range(0, len(queries))):
        x, y = query_to_list(conn, query)
        fig.line(x, y, color='#88%02x88' % (255 // (num + 1)))
        
    show(fig)

Given the two queries, we can see that they differ slightly. This is fine because they both start with slightly different initial conditions due to the random start.

In [26]:
plot_queries(db,
            ["select time, max(heat) from fortran group by time",
             "select time, max(heat) from scala group by time"], y_scale="log")
In [ ]:

Hey, that's interesting, they seem to cross over. What's the difference between the two over time?

We'll create two "views" -- one that is the max heat for each over time. Views can be thought of as lazy queries, or on demand queries, or variable bindings of names to queries. This will make our query easier to read.

View of the Fortran heat over time.

In [27]:
cursor.execute("""create view mfortran as 
select time, max(heat) as m from fortran group by time""")
Out[27]:
<apsw.Cursor at 0x7efcc447d030>

View of the Scala heat over time.

In [28]:
cursor.execute("""create view mscala as 
select time, max(heat) as m from scala group by time""")
Out[28]:
<apsw.Cursor at 0x7efcc447d030>

Joins!¶

Query the difference between the two values, where the times are the same. How to we make sure the subtraction between the two time steps are the same, with where mfortran.time = mscala.time.

In full SQLite syntax, this query would be select mscala.time, mfortran.m - mscala.m from mfortran INNER JOIN mscala ON mfortran.time = mscala.time You don't have to specify INNER JOIN in modern SQL syntax, as it is assumed by the WHERE clause.

This is an equijoin, we are joining the two tables together based on a common value matching on a column, i.e., creating a new table by definining a new relationship between the two tables.

If you were to do this manually, you'd have to write, basically, a doubly-nested for loop, matching time steps and doing the difference on the matched time step.

In pseudocode, if I were to manually program this, it would be:

list = []
for all time steps
  for all fortran values
     f = get max heat
  for all scala values
     s = get max heat
  diff = f - s
  list = list + (diff, t)
In [29]:
plot_query(db, """select mscala.time, mfortran.m - mscala.m from mfortran, mscala 
where mfortran.time = mscala.time""")

Hey, that's pretty interesting, there's a cross-over point minimum. What time step is that at?

In [30]:
cursor.execute("""select mscala.time, min(mfortran.m - mscala.m) from mfortran, mscala 
where mfortran.time = mscala.time""").fetchall()
Out[30]:
[(1700, -6.151003345403135e-05)]

Also, we can put both data sets into one table, and then be able to query by attribute!

In [31]:
cursor.execute("""create view both as
select *, 'Fortran' as type from fortran
union all
select *, 'Scala' as type from scala
""")
Out[31]:
<apsw.Cursor at 0x7efcc447d030>

Using this newfound ability, we can easily create a difference image for time step 1700 to see how they differ.

Though, technically, we could have just done the same thing with the two original tables in the subquery, but I am just showing off that we can now restrict by table, by having a table name as an attribute.

In [32]:
image_query(db, """
select sum(heat) from 
(select heat as heat, i, j, time from both where type = 'Fortran'
 union all
 select -heat as heat, i, j, time from both where type = 'Scala')
where time = 1700 group by i, j
""", x, y)
